[[Image:Oonimasumishiritsuhiko-jinja Ishi-toro.jpg|thumb|200px|A row of consecrated [[lanterns|stone lanterns]] lined up behind the second torii gate (August 2012)]]'''Tazami Shiritsuhiko Shrine'' jalink|Isoshi-gun|Q1155036}}{{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Tawaramoto Town|Q1203159}}. {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi-sha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} ({{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and {{ill|lt=Modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is a prefectural shrine. It is generally called ''Tajinja'' (Ojinja), and is also written as Tasha, Taza Shrine, Taisha, and Oosha. {{ill|lt=company name|Q11588355|WD=Q11588355|1=company name}} The sign reads ``Ta{{Unicode|㘴}}Yashiritsuhiko Shrine.''

=== Enshrined God ===
The following four gods are {{ill|lt=Enshrined Deities|Q11591100|WD=Q11591100|lt=Main Enshrined Deities|1=Saijin}}.
* Daiichi Shrine Kamiwa Iwayohiko ({{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}: Father of Kami Yaimimi no Mikoto)
* Second shrine {{ill|lt=Kamiyaimimi no Mikoto|Q11588756|WD=Q11588756|1=Kamuyaimimi}} (Emperor Jimmu {{ill|lt=Prince|Q12886381|WD=Q12886381|1=Imperial Prince}})
* Third Shrine Kaminuma Kawami no Mikoto ({{ill|lt=Emperor Suisei|Q313321|WD=Q313321|1=Emperor Suizei}}: younger brother of Kamiyami no Mikoto)
* Fourth Shrine Himemikami ({{ill|lt=Tamayoribime (Hyuga mythology)|Q3082751|WD=Q3082751|lt=Tamayorihime no Mikoto|1=Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)}}: {{ill|lt=grandparents|Q167918|WD=Q167918|lt=grandmother|1=Grandparent}} of the god Yaimimi no Mikoto)

In addition, {{ill|lt=Taian Manso|Q384705|WD=Q384705|1=Ō no Yasumaro}}, who compiled the ``{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|WD=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}'', is also enshrined here. This area was the base of the {{ill|lt=Ta clan|Q11430816|WD=Q11430816|1=Ō clan}}, and is believed to have been dedicated to the Ta clan's {{ill|lt=tutelary deity|Q767655|WD=Q767655|lt=ancestor deity|1=Ujigami}}, Kami Yaimimi no Mikoto.

In the ``{{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmecho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' it is written as ``{{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}{{ill|lt=Toichi District|Q11405036|WD=Q11405036|1=Toichi district}} Tazami Shiritsuhiko Shrine 2.''In {{ill|lt=Hisayasu|Q1193860|WD=Q1193860|1=Kyūan}}5 years ({{ill|lt=1149|Q19638|WD=Q19638|1=1149}}), our company {{ill|lt=Negi|Q11594490|WD=Q11594490|1=Negi}}{{ill|lt=Asaomi|Q4807592|WD=Q4807592|1=Ason}} In the ``Tajingu Shujinsho'' submitted by Tsunemaro to the {{ill|lt=Kokushi|Q1351234|WD=Q1351234|1=Kokushi (official)}}, it lists the following two shrines, and it is also written that Mihishirihikohimenokami, based on the company's name, is the second shrine in the Engishiki Jinmyocho.
* Chinko Sakatsuhiko no Mikoto (Utsu no Miko Sakatsuhiko no Mikoto) Imperial Statue Qiongyokuza {{ill|lt=Kawachi Province|Q1047150|WD=Q1047150|1=Kawachi Province}}{{ill|lt=Takayasu (Yao City)#Takayasu District|Q11669131|WD=Q11669131|lt=Takayasu District|1=Takayasu}} Same deity as Kasukabe Zauzu Mikono Shrine
* Amatsuoya Sakatsuhime no Mikoto Same deity as the sacred Enkyoza {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Omikami Takaza Shrine/Iwato Shrine|Q11442907|WD=Q11442907|lt=Kasukabeza Amaterasu Ojinsha|1=Amaterasu Ōmikami Takakura Shrine & Iwato Shrine}}

{{ill|lt=Original|Q1145754|WD=Q1145754|1=Genbun}}2 ({{ill|lt=1737|Q6993|WD=Q6993|1=1737}}), it has the current four seats, but {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji|1=UNKNOWN}} era's ``Shinto Detail Book'' states that the first and fourth shrines of the main shrine are treated as {{ill|lt=Setsusha|Q1071160|WD=Q1071160|lt=Setsusha|1=Setsumatsusha}}, and the two main deities enshrined are Kamiyami no Mikoto and Kaminuma Kawami no Mikoto.According to the company's name, it is a shrine dedicated to Mishiritsuhiko, but this shrine is thought to refer to the god Yaimimi no Mikoto. Although he was the eldest son of Emperor Jinmu, he handed over the {{ill|lt=Imperial Throne|Q1981690|WD=Q1981690|1=Chrysanthemum Throne}} to his younger brother, so he is also called ``Mishiritsuhiko'' which means ``retired.''

=== History ===
{{ill|lt=Japanese Mythology|Q814158|WD=Q814158|lt=Kikiki Mythology|1=Japanese mythology}} says, ``{{ill|lt=Kami Yaimimi no Mikoto|Q11588756|WD=Q11588756|1=Kamuyaimimi}} passed on the imperial throne to his younger brother, and he himself enshrined {{ill|lt=Amatsukami/Kunitsukami|Q11442793|WD=Q11442793|lt=Jingi|1=Amatsukami and Kunitsukami}},'' and this is the beginning of our company. In {{ill|lt=Emperor Suisei|Q313321|WD=Q313321|1=Emperor Suizei}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=6th century BC|Q25296|WD=Q25296|lt=580 BC|1=6th century BC}}), Kamiyami no Mikoto built a mansion in Kasuga Prefecture (later {{ill|lt=Toichi-gun|Q11405036|WD=Q11405036|lt=Toichi Prefecture|1=Toichi district}}). There he established {{ill|lt=Shinryō|Q60587|WD=Q60587|1=Himorogi}}{{ill|lt=Iwaza|Q11587880|WD=Q11587880|lt=Iwakyo|1=Iwakura rock}}, personally presided over the rituals, and enshrined the gods of Dainichi, the distant ancestor of Kasuga {{ill|lt=prefectural head|Q10746487|WD=Q10746487|1=Agatanushi}}. It is said that in {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|WD=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}} 7th year ({{ill|lt=91 BC|Q40968|WD=Q40968|1=91 BC}}), the shrine was remodeled and the Amatsu Nichiron Gyoku no Mikoto and Tensho Kagami Tsurugi gods were offered there.{{ill|lt=Shosoin Documents|Q11545362|WD=Q11545362|1=Shōsōin Documents}}'s {{ill|lt=Tenpyo|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}}2nd year ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=730th|1=UNKNOWN}}) {{ill|lt=Yamato Country|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}{{ill|lt=Sei Tax Book|Q11545592|WD=Q11545592|1=Sei Tax Book}} "Daikobe Inaichimangobo It is written as ``柱一萬三捌集肆笀', and it is written as ``柱一萬 連 連 連 連 連 ＧＧ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ Ｇ properly The {{ill|lt=rice|Q161426|WD=Q161426|lt=rice|1=Oryza sativa}} owned by (Private House)|Q11589711|Kobe}} had a large economic power compared to other companies, with 10,690 bundles and 9 bundles, including 4 bundles of 138 for {{ill|lt=tax|Q847178|WD=Q847178|lt=rice tax|1=rice tax}}.In "{{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmecho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}," Yamato Province{{ill|lt=Toichi-gun|Q11405036|WD=Q11405036|1=Toichi district}} It is written as ``Tazami Shiritsuhiko Shrine 2'', and is listed as {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}, {{ill|lt=Monthly Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|lt=Monthly|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}}, {{jalink |Ainamesai|Q11581944|Ainame}}, {{ill|lt=Ninamesai|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|lt=Niname|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}'s {{ill|lt=Heihaku|Q11481885|WD=Q11481885|1=Hanpei}}. {{ill|lt=Eiji|Q1194167|WD=Q1194167|1=Eiji (era)}} In the first year of the year ({{ill|lt=1141|Q19613|WD=Q19613|1=1141}}), in the "Draft of Notes to the Many Shrines" }}, and the {{ill|lt=plaque|Q5358873|WD=Q5358873|1=biane}} of ``Shoichii {{ill|lt=Order of Honor|Q17990718|WD=Q17990718|lt=Order of First Class|1=Japanese honors system}} Daimyojin'' is displayed on the first {{ill|lt=torii|Q234731|WD=Q234731|1=Torii}} and the second torii. The first torii gate is located along the Terakawa River, beyond the {{ill|lt=Kintetsu Kashihara Line|Q2491066|WD=Q2491066|1=Kashihara Line}} tracks, about 800m east of the shrine.In ancient times it was called Kasuga Shrine, and the current shrine territory is approximately 10,000 {{ill|lt=square meters|Q25343|WD=Q25343|lt=m<sup>2</sup>|1=Square metre}}, but according to "Yamato Shiryo" (era name)|Q1192853|Tenbun}}21 ({{ill|lt=1552|Q6565|WD=Q6565|1=1552}}), 6 {{jalink|towns} surrounding the local lord, {{ill|lt=Toichi Tokatsu|Q11405030|WD=Q11405030|1=Tōchi Tōkatsu}} (Unit)|Q1185752|Town}} It is said that a square piece of land (approximately 420,000 m<sup>2</sup>) was donated, and there were torii gates on all sides.

During the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} period, it was promoted to a local shrine of {{ill|lt=Tamura|Q17174841|WD=Q17174841|1=Ō}}, and in {{ill|lt=1923|Q2169|WD=Q2169|1=1923}} ({{ill|lt=Taisho|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}}12) it was promoted to a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}.

Behind the main shrine is a small hill called ``Jinbuzuka,'' which is thought to be an ancient ritual site or {{ill|lt=kofun|Q1141225|WD=Q1141225|1=Kofun}}.

{{ill|lt=1972|Q2476|WD=Q2476|1=1972}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}47), {{ill|lt=Asuka River behind our company (Nara Prefecture)|Q11665966|WD=Q11665966|lt=Asuka River|1=Asuka River}} Ruins (multiple ruins) from the {{ill|lt=Jomon period|Q52824|WD=Q52824|1=Jōmon period}} to {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|WD=Q459939|1=Kofun period}} were discovered within the precincts during embankment construction.

=== Precincts ===
* Main shrine - Four shrine shrines {{ill|lt=Kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|WD=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}} lined up in the east and west. In {{ill|lt=1977|Q2481|WD=Q2481|1=1977}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}52), the {{ill|lt=cypress bark roof|Q90373477|WD=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} was changed to a copper plate roof.
** First Hall (designated by Nara Prefecture {{ill|lt=tangible cultural property|Q2901860|WD=Q2901860|1=Tangible Cultural Property (Japan)}}) - Rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}20 ({{ill|lt=1735|Q6984|WD=Q6984|1=1735}}).
** Second Hall (Tangible Cultural Property designated by Nara Prefecture) - Rebuilt in 1735.
** Third Hall (Tangible Cultural Property designated by Nara Prefecture) - Rebuilt in Kyoho and {{ill|lt=Horeki|Q1194397|WD=Q1194397|1=Hōreki}} years ({{ill|lt=1716|Q6892|WD=Q6892|1=1716}} - {{ill|lt=1764|Q7659|WD=Q7659|1=1764}}).
** Fourth Hall (Tangible Cultural Property designated by Nara Prefecture) - Rebuilt during the Kyoho period (1716-1764).
* Middle gate
* Hall of worship
* Tajinja Shrine Museum
* Shrine office
** Shrine office front gate

